    The crash is caused by unbounded recursion in fib.                          
                                                                                
    The relevant code is:                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
       return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
       auto const n = 100;                                                      
       std::cout << "fib(" << n << ") = " << fib(n);                            
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    main calls:                                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     fib(100)                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Inside fib, there is no base case. Every call to fib(n) immediately calls   
    more recursive fib calls:                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    So the call chain begins roughly like this:                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     fib(100)                                                                   
       fib(99)                                                                  
         fib(98)                                                                
           fib(97)                                                              
             ...                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Eventually n reaches values where a normal Fibonacci implementation would   
    stop:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     fib(1)                                                                     
     fib(0)                                                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But this implementation does not stop there. It continues:                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     fib(0)                                                                     
       fib(-1)                                                                  
         fib(-2)                                                                
           fib(-3)                                                              
             ...                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That matches the stack trace:                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     fib(n = -261269)                                                           
     fib(n = -261268)                                                           
     fib(n = -261267)                                                           
     ...                                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Those negative values are present because n has been repeatedly             
    decremented by the recursive call fib(n - 1). Since there is no condition   
    that returns for n == 0, n == 1, or invalid negative values, recursion      
    continues until the process exhausts its stack.                             
                                                                                
    The crash:                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=2, address=0x16f603ffc)                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
    is consistent with a stack overflow on macOS. The program keeps creating    
    recursive stack frames until it touches memory beyond the valid stack       
    region.                                                                     
                                                                                
    The immediate defect is here:                                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
       return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    There is no terminating condition.                                          
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix is to add Fibonacci base cases:                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int fib(int n) {                                                           
       if (n <= 1) {                                                            
         return n;                                                              
       }                                                                        
                                                                                
       return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);                                          
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    However, this is only a partial fix. It prevents the infinite recursion     
    for nonnegative inputs, but there are still two deeper problems:            
                                                                                
     1 fib(100) is far too expensive with the naive recursive implementation.   
       It takes exponential time.                                               
     2 The return type int cannot store fib(100). The value is:                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     354224848179261915075                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That is much larger than a 32-bit int, and even larger than a 64-bit        
    signed integer.                                                             
                                                                                
    So a more complete root-cause fix would be to use an iterative              
    implementation and a type large enough to store the result. For example,    
    using boost::multiprecision::cpp_int:                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <iostream>                                                        
     #include <stdexcept>                                                       
     #include <boost/multiprecision/cpp_int.hpp>                                
                                                                                
     using boost::multiprecision::cpp_int;                                      
                                                                                
     cpp_int fib(int n) {                                                       
       if (n < 0) {                                                             
         throw std::invalid_argument("fib is undefined for negative n");        
       }                                                                        
                                                                                
       cpp_int a = 0;                                                           
       cpp_int b = 1;                                                           
                                                                                
       for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {                                            
         cpp_int next = a + b;                                                  
         a = b;                                                                 
         b = next;                                                              
       }                                                                        
                                                                                
       return a;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
       auto const n = 100;                                                      
       std::cout << "fib(" << n << ") = " << fib(n) << '\n';                    
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This version:                                                               
                                                                                
     • Terminates for valid inputs.                                             
     • Rejects negative inputs explicitly.                                      
     • Avoids stack overflow by using iteration instead of recursion.           
     • Correctly computes fib(100) without integer overflow.                    
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Use an iterative Fibonacci implementation with explicit input validation    
    and a sufficiently large integer type:                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <iostream>                                                        
     #include <stdexcept>                                                       
     #include <boost/multiprecision/cpp_int.hpp>                                
                                                                                
     using boost::multiprecision::cpp_int;                                      
                                                                                
     cpp_int fib(int n) {                                                       
       if (n < 0) {                                                             
         throw std::invalid_argument("fib is undefined for negative n");        
       }                                                                        
                                                                                
       cpp_int a = 0;                                                           
       cpp_int b = 1;                                                           
                                                                                
       for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {                                            
         cpp_int next = a + b;                                                  
         a = b;                                                                 
         b = next;                                                              
       }                                                                        
                                                                                
       return a;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main() {                                                               
       auto const n = 100;                                                      
       std::cout << "fib(" << n << ") = " << fib(n) << '\n';                    
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
